article.description: One night after scoring 23 points in her WNBA debut, Tamika Catchings had 27 to lead the Indiana Fever to a second straight win over the Detroit Shock, 78-65 on Sunday.

related.title: After 17 months of waiting, Catchings proves her worth
related.headline: After 17 months of waiting, Catchings proves her worth

article.headline: Catchings scores 27 in second WNBA game
article.linkText: Catchings catches on as Fever roll over Shock
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Tamika Catchings knows how to make an entrance.

	   One night after scoring 23 points in her WNBA debut, Catchings
had 27 to lead the Indiana Fever to a second straight win over the
Detroit Shock, 78-65 on Sunday.

	   ``She's played two games, and she's already a star in this
league,'' Shock coach Greg Williams said. ``She can do everything
on the floor and we haven't been able to do anything to stop her.''

	   Catchings, who missed the 2001 season with a knee injury, was
12-for-12 from the free-throw line, two short of Lisa Leslie's WNBA
record. The Fever were 29-for-31 overall.

	   ``She makes a huge difference for us at both ends of the
floor,'' Fever coach Nell Fortner said. ``Whether she is scoring or
playing great defense, she is a tremendous competitor.''

	   Nikki McCray added 21 points for Indiana (2-0), which has beaten
Detroit (0-3) five straight times.

	   ``This has been a lot of fun,'' said McCray, who came to the
Fever in a pre-draft trade with Washington. ``This team really
understands my role.''

	   The victory, Indiana's second over Detroit in two nights,
spoiled the Shock's home opener. Attendance was announced at 5,681,
but the crowd appeared much smaller.

	   ``Obviously, we hoped for a bigger crowd, but we need to win
some games before we can expect the fans to get excited,'' Williams
said. ``I'm disappointed that with eight road games in our first
10, we wasted one of them like this.''

	   Wendy Palmer led Detroit with 16 points, Astou Ndiaye-Diatta
added 15 and rookie Swin Cash had 14.

	   ``This is a tough adjustment,'' said Cash, who played last
season for undefeated national champion Connecticut. ``But that's
part of being a rookie. I'm learning new stuff every night.''

	   Cash spent much of the night guarding Catchings, and was
surprised at how much she had improved since leaving Tennessee
after the 2000-01 season.

	   ``I played against Tamika in college, and she's much better
now,'' Cash said. ``We did a decent job against her, but she killed
us from the line. We can't just keep putting here there.''

	   The Fever used a 13-2 run to take a 52-46 lead with 12:30 left.
Catchings scored seven during the run and Malcolm added four.

	   The Shock cut it to 56-55, but Indiana answered with a 12-0
surge to go up 68-55 with 3:33 left.

	   ``We are realizing that every team is going to make a run
against us, and the important thing is how you respond,'' Catchings
said. ``We've been able to pull each other together in these two
games and answer the runs that other teams have made.''
